What You Parse in RF2

The important RF2 tables are:

1. Concept File

Contains:

active concepts
IDs
status

Example:

Left knee joint pain
2. Relationship File

This is the important one.

It contains:

IS-A hierarchy
defining attributes

Examples:

finding site → left knee structure
associated morphology
laterality
occurrence
Pure Ontology Traversal Algorithm
Step 1 — Get defining attributes of seed concept

From RF2 relationships collect:

finding site = left knee joint
laterality = left
clinical finding = pain

These become the semantic signature.

Step 2 — Traverse IS-A parents upward

Using:

typeId = 116680003 (IS-A)

walk parent chain upward.

Step 3 — At each ancestor, inspect relationships

Check whether ancestor still preserves:

same finding site,
same laterality,
same structure,
same role groups.
Stopping Rule

Stop when a defining attribute disappears or generalizes.

Example:

Concept	Laterality	Knee	Joint
Left knee joint pain	YES	YES	YES
Left knee pain	YES	YES	NO
Disorder of left knee	YES	YES	NO
Structure of left knee	YES	YES	NO
Knee structure	NO	YES	NO

Traversal stops before:

Knee structure

because:

laterality vanished.
Why This Works Better Than IC

IC only approximates:

semantic broadening.

RF2 relationships explicitly encode:

semantic broadening.

So you can directly observe ontology meaning changes instead of inferring them statistically.

Important RF2 Fields

You mainly need:

RF2 Field	Purpose
sourceId	child concept
destinationId	target concept
typeId	relationship type
characteristicTypeId	stated/inferred
relationshipGroup	semantic grouping
Relationship Types to Monitor

Especially important:

Relationship	Meaning
Finding site	anatomy
Associated morphology	pathology
Laterality	left/right
Procedure site	procedures
Due to	causation
Severity	qualifiers
Recommended Logic

Instead of:

“largest semantic drop”

do:

“highest ancestor preserving all defining RF2 relationships.”

That is:

cleaner,
ontology-native,
deterministic,
explainable,
fully RF2-driven.
Even Better: Use Role Groups

In SNOMED, meaning is often encoded via:

relationshipGroup

You should compare:

grouped semantic patterns,
not individual relationships alone.

Example:

Group:

finding site = left knee
morphology = inflammation

If the parent breaks or removes the group:

semantic boundary crossed.

This is much more robust than IC.

